Barack Obama becomes the fourth US president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama comes to Oslo, Norway, for 26 hours to become the fourth US president in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
In addition, he receives the diploma as well as the medal and a check for 1.4 million dollars for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The head of the White House arrives tomorrow together with his wife Michelle in the Nordweg metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First, he visits the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time ever with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple then scheduled a meeting with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit culminates with the ceremony at which Obama takes over the prestigious award.
He receives this as the fourth US president, but only as the third to receive the prize directly in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when accepting the prize.
The president does not want to avoid this issue, because he knows that he is taking the prize as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
A few days ago, he stepped up the war effort by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forgets to emphasize.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gold medal, diploma and check for ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money to charity, but he has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The programme of events will include a banquet with the President and his wife, which will be attended by Norway's King and Queen, the Prime Minister and 250 other invited guests.
Obama was very cautious about the price from the beginning.
He stated, for example, that he felt that he did not quite deserve the prize.
He also repeated several times that it is the price not only for him, but for all those who aspire to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that this was for him "call to action".
