USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is almost comical with what student ambition Barack Obama, the president with his reputation for the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor on Afghanistan, whom he himself considered the stupidest.
When he finally sweated out his eagerly awaited Afghanistan doctrine, it turned out that he copied it via copy paper from the Bush-Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not only did he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, he even used the name of the Bush Declaration of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: "New Way Forward" without hesitation.
Three years ago, he himself criticized Bush's idea of sending fresh troop contingents to civil war-torn Iraq as an "irresponsible and carastrophic decision."
Months that followed, however, showed that Bush's strategy, based on military recommendations, was the only possible and very successful to the extent that Iraq is no longer talked about in the news today.
This has not improved Bush's reputation, because objectively he has left his successor with a much more grateful starting point than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will be repeated.
The military have again asked him to increase the troop contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghanistan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even despite the subordination habits harshly criticized the hesitant shooters in the White House.
He called for 40,000 soldiers to reverse the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but did not come up with a better idea and so he cheated the general of 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe, he has pressed the commitment for another 5,000, even if he himself originally expected at least 10,000.
What is most problematic about the whole Obama strategy is his plan to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and complete this process within three years. The whole Obama doctrine leaves more questions than answers.
Some doubt that the halved increase will have the same effect as the measure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal war of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well structured, and its leaders honor its values.
The Afghan situation is characterized by the contraindication - no one can be relied on and no agreements are kept.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, who are used to changing their minds every day.
The political institutions, even if they were formally correct, remain only fictitious buildings, behind which the patriarchal trunk relations will continue to proliferate.
The balancing of interests between the different ethnic groups is unusually complicated, especially because of the complexity of the circumstances, which further complicates the Pakistan and Iran influences.
Also, the construction of an "effective state", which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, is very unrealistic.
Time horizon of Obama's strategy alienated by its voluntarism
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only deteriorated and is now on the verge of explosion.
To believe that the little soldiers who have broken out in the war cry about the "early return" create a miracle here, can only a truly romantic soul who is not impressed by facts.
From a political point of view, setting the date for troop withdrawal is sheer irresponsibility, because the Taliban will take it as the indirect confession of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that Europeans' willingness to take part in the fighting in Afghanistan is running out.
Europe's politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is linked to the war in the Hindu Kush foothills.
Another possible factor that can radically influence the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not affect the Iranians, a very difficult question arises for the United States as to whether the problem cannot be solved with troops.
This question must be answered in the period in which America proceeds after Obama to the victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
But any solution will also mean a dramatic turn in the Afghan situation.
The only consolation for Barack Obama is the fact that there are still three years left until the presidential election, leaving enough time for him to resort to a different strategy, if it proves to be a total failure.
