Vaccination against pneumococci free of charge and voluntary
Imfung against pneumococci changes the usual from January.
It should be the first to be free and voluntary for families.
But there are already voices that mandatory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free pneumococcal vaccination are culminating.
The drug institute already sets the maximum prices of the vaccines that health insurance companies have to pay.
The experts are also aware of the vaccination procedure.
New vaccination
Free vaccines for August children
From January, children born on August 2 last year and later can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococci.
The condition is that they have not yet received a vaccine dose.
Anyone who has already started the vaccination last year or earlier must also pay for further revaccination themselves.
The first dose of vaccine must be given between the 3rd and 5th month of the child's life.
Last year, a quarter of families had their children vaccinated against pneumococci.
The parents paid 1600 crowns and more for one dose.
Four doses are required to vaccinate the youngest children.
Overall, experts estimate that health insurance companies spend 300,000 to 450,000 crowns per year on vaccine doses.
But they save on the treatment that the children would need without vaccination.
So far, the state has spent about 500,000 per year on all area vaccinations of children.
The compulsory vaccination was introduced with the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococci cause otitis media, but also serious infections including meningitis and blood poisoning.
According to examinations in hospitals, up to 28 children up to the age of 10 die each year due to pneumococcal infections.
Outside the Czech Republic, compulsory vaccination of children against pneumococci has been introduced in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
At the same time, it is said that this vaccination could be mandatory in the future.
From January, this should be paid by the insurance companies and voluntary.
That the compulsory vaccination would be better, mentioned, for example, the head of the citizens' association Nahlas, Rudolf Kalovsky.
His association is already promoting pneumococcal vaccination in the long term.
The experts at the international conference in which our association was involved were not very satisfied with the fact that we have voluntary vaccination.
This is not entirely ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that we have managed to achieve at least that.
I believe that this is the path we have to take now, Kalovsky said.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the vaccination procedure against pneumococci.
At this moment we are not considering this at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sesen.
