Still them and us
Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters have voted to ban minarets and concerns about the supposed Islamization of Europe are widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written an informed and considered report on whether Muslims can — and will be — integrated — into one of Europe's most avowedly secularized societies.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work, "Why the French Don't Like Headscarves" (2006), an elegant and densely argued study of a controversy that divided and occupied the country for a decade and a half, and whose effects can still be felt today.
Bowen's latest book offers a broader and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what the politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer what Bowen calls "Islamic freedom" to France's 5 to 6 million Muslims.
He is a good listener, he reflects debates between teachers and students on the issues that worry them most.
Should a Muslim marry (or both) in a mosque or town hall?
Should young Muslims be taught about evolution and gay rights?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest-rate banking system to obtain a mortgage?
It is these seemingly mundane affairs, he claims, that make up daily life, in contrast to the political dramas that preoccupy the media.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a well-known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, a Swiss-born Arab-Muslim scholar and academic.
This new generation is trying to open the debate about how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen on the other in a modern secular society.
They don't have all the arguments on their side.
Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists Bowen interviewed are mostly at odds with their Salafi counterparts – advocates of purist Sunni Islam linked to Saudi Arabia – who now have a small but influential presence among Europe's Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires give and take on both sides.
He questions the extent to which French policymakers (and the intellectual elite who so passionately guard the separation of church and state) are truly committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may be treated harsher than Catholics, Protestants, and Jews, who in turn have had to make their historic compromise with secular republicanism.
He sees a "tightening of the screws of values" rather than a growing pragmatism.
Can Islam be French? After reading this book, one is inclined to say "Yes, but not yet".
