Richard Ellis, an author and illustrator, draws in "On Thin Ice" a natural history of the icon of the North, the polar bear.
Well versed in the complicated history and politics of whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers who proved themselves hunting polar bears.
Admiral Nelson's encounter with a polar bear as a brave 14-year-old ensign at sea who fought only with the butt of his musket is certainly a legend, but others are true.
Young bears caught swimming behind the bodies of their recently killed mothers were taken to zoos and circuses.
A circus performance at the beginning of the 20th century showed 75 polar bears at one performance.
Even today, zoos still typically have one millionth of the habitat of a wild animal. The climate is rarely suitable: the polar bear in Singapore turned green from the algae that grow in the hollow hairs of its fur.
