Referring to the accounts of other authors and historians, Ellis often returns to the threat hunters pose to the survival of the species.
Although banned in Norway, America and Russia, killing continues in Greenland and Canada, where hunters in helicopters and snowmobile-driving Inuit use powerful assault rifles to hunt down their prey.
Ironically, it is in the waters to the north of these two hunting nations that the ice will last the longest.
In his new book, After the Ice, Alun Anderson, a former editor of New Scientist, offers a clear and disturbing description of Arctic science and a gripping glimpse into how the future might unfold.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the rapidity of the changes.
However, this is not due to a lack of explanations.
Fridtjof Nansen's pioneering journeys at the end of the 19th and beginning of the 20th century gave an idea of the turbulence of the pack ice for the first time.
During the Cold War, submarines measured the shifting ridges when driving under.
A useful addition is satellite surveys and the large-scale deployment of probes on icebergs, but still much is achieved by intrepid people camping outside in the cold.
Anderson takes a look into the strange, tiny world of the tributary system within the Arctic ice, formed by saltwater rivulets that are compressed during freezing.
But, from the bear on the ice to the microscopic wonders in the ice, everyone is threatened when the summer ice passes, which is expected between 2013 and 2050.
