Marines were among the 6,000 who laid wreaths in Arlington
Corporal De'Angello Robinson traveled seven hours by bus to lay a single wreath on the grave of a soldier he had never met.
For him and the other Marines who made the journey from Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina, to Arlington National Cemetery to decorate graves, the day was a tribute to the men and women in whose footsteps they followed.
In a few months, from wherever we are brought back, we could be, Robinson said of the fallen soldiers.
If we were, I wish someone would do the same for me, so I try to show my respect.
He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who gathered Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans in several sections of Arlington Cemetery.
Morrill Worcester, owner of the funeral wreath manufacturer Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, started this tradition in 1992 when he and several others decided to decorate several hundred graves at the cemetery in Arlington.
It's now an 18-year-old tradition and Morrill and his wife, Karen, who make this trip every year, stop at various towns along the way to hold events dedicated to people in the military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcesters also formed a non-profit organization, Wreaths Across America (wreaths throughout America), which has expanded the event to other states.
This year, volunteers laid more than 16,000 wreaths on the graves at Arlington Cemetery, in areas around the Pentagon, on graves at Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, at Battery Park in New York, and at the United Airlines Flight 93 Memorial in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second time, the Walmart Foundation donated more than $150,000 to purchase and transport the wreaths.
Charleen Hunt, 70, of Westminster, said she made the trip to Arlington in memory of her husband, a late professional soldier.
Although her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said, this is her way of giving back to those who made sacrifices.
She said this is a small contribution to how we civilians can support our soldiers.
It's like visiting a family tomb.
Wrapped in layers of warm clothing, the volunteers wandered across the extensive lawns and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers targeted older graves from World War 1 and 2 and the Vietnam War, as these are not visited as often as the newer graves, according to the organizers.
The mood was cheerful, children were playing and couples held hands as they carried the fresh pine branches to the graying tombstones.
Each round wreath was dark green with a small red bow attached to the upper part.
Section 60, which is located nearby and where mainly veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried, remained almost quiet.
The United Service Organizations donated 1,000 wreaths to decorate this section, but the gloomy mood of the current wars filled this area.
Some wept openly, others prayed, and families and friends clung to each other in the icy air.
Some read aloud the names carved in stone, while others bent down to small black-and-white place cards that had been stuck in the damp mud for those whose tombstones were not yet finished.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers who shed bitter tears in front of her son's grave.
She drove 8 hours from Zanesfield, Ohio, to visit the gravesite of Naval Infrastructure Sergeant David Shane Spicer, who was killed in battle in July.
No one should ever forget why we are free..., my son paid for it, she said.
"When I've been away for a long time, I want someone to remember him."
U.S. government contractor detained by Cuban authorities
The Cuban government has detained a U.S. government contractor who sold mobile phones and notebook computers in the country, State Department officials said Saturday.
The contractor, who has not yet been identified, works for Bethesda-based Development Alternatives Inc.
The company works on projects for clients such as USAID, the U.S. Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
Consular officials from the U.S. Interests Section in Havana are trying to gain access to the detainee who was arrested on Dec. 5.
The specific charges have not yet been made public, although under Cuban law, a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be arrested for almost anything, on charges of "endangerment."
All so-called counterrevolutionary activities, which include light protests and critical writings, carry a risk of arrest.
Anti-government graffiti and statements are considered a serious crime.
Cuba has a growing community of bloggers, led by popular reporter Yoani Sánchez, who often describes how she and her husband are persecuted and attacked by government officials.
Sánchez has repeatedly asked for permission to leave the country to receive prizes, but this has always been refused.
The arrest of an American contractor is likely to increase tensions between the Castro Brother's communist government in Cuba and the Obama administration, which had sought a "slow" rapprochement to improve relations with the island.
News of the arrest was first reported Friday night by the New York Times.
The new U.S. policy emphasizes that the United States will provide something in return if the Cuban government takes concrete steps in this direction, such as releasing political prisoners and creating more space for opposition.
Mobile phones and notebooks are legal in Cuba, although they are new and sought-after products in a country where the average salary of a government employee is $15 per month.
The Cuban government has only been allowing ordinary citizens to buy a mobile phone since this year, they are mainly used to send text messages, as a 15-minute phone call would cost a day's wage.
Internet use is extremely limited on the island.
It is in expensive hotels and there accessible to foreign visitors and at some government agencies, such as universities.
Cubans who want to log in often have to report their names to the government.
Access to many websites is restricted.
In Cuba, the arrest of an American is rare.
Most of the few U.S. citizens in prison in Cuba are behind bars for crimes such as drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbena, the spokeswoman for the U.S. Interests Section in Havana.
Berbena said she could not provide any further information on the arrest.
The arrest and detention are clearly false.
One activity that would be legal in any other free society — giving away free cell phones — is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivanco, head of the U.S. section of Human Rights Watch, which recently issued a tough report on freedom in Cuba titled "New Castro, Same Cuba," a reference to Raul Castro's inauguration as the country's leader.  who replaced the sick older brother Fidel.
Vivanco said that very often the defendants are arrested, convicted and imprisoned within a day.
He said that any solution would probably be political and that the Cuban government often provokes a negative reaction in the United States, just as the two countries are moving towards each other for more dialogue.
Pakistani officials reveal plan to send men to Afghanistan
Pakistani authorities on Saturday discovered an alleged leader in a conspiracy aimed at sending five men from Northern Virginia to Afghanistan to kill U.S. soldiers, saying they hope the case could help uncover an extensive network of terrorist recruiters who scour the internet for radicalized young men.
Investigators said they were looking for an opaque insurgent known as Saifullah, who invited the men to Pakistan after locating them because one of them had made affirmative comments on terrorist attacks on the internet video site YouTube.
Saifullah became the leader of these men upon their arrival in Pakistan, trying to help them reach the remote area in Pakistan's tribal belt, which is home to al Qaeda and its terrorist training camps.
But a Pakistani intelligence official briefed on the matter said Saturday that Saifullah could not convince al-Qaeda leaders that the men were not part of a CIA conspiracy to infiltrate the terrorist network.
As a result, they were held for days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far from the inhospitable mountains in the northwest, which have become a terrorist haven.
They were seen as part of a covert operation.
That's why they were rejected, said the government official, who wished to remain anonymous due to the sensitivity of the matter.
The government official said the men were by no means discouraged and continued to try to get the right recommendations to gain access to al-Qaeda camps when they were detained by Pakistani law enforcement authorities.
The case of the five men — who remain in Pakistan and are being questioned by the FBI — underscores the crucial role of recruiters in identifying future terrorists and, perhaps more importantly, in deciding who is trustworthy.
Since the attacks of September 11, 2001, U.S. intelligence has made it a matter of the utmost urgency to house human assets within al Qaeda.
The organization's recruiters act as gatekeepers, not letting in those whose commitment to holy war is not serious enough and those who might be spies.
American would-be recruits are subjected to special scrutiny by al-Qaeda, analysts said.
But because of their potential access to U.S. targets and their propaganda value, they are also seen as tremendously attractive to the group.
Evan Kohlmann, senior analyst at the NEFA Foundation, based in the US, said terrorist groups have also become much more cautious in recent years about who they allow access to, as US intelligence agencies have become experts in their recruitment methods.
If you're trying to infiltrate someone into these groups, what better way to go than to follow the recruitment model that so many have already followed?"
The model is now much more based on the Internet.
Tens of thousands of demonstrators in Copenhagen demand climate "action"
Tens of thousands of demonstrators marched through the streets here on Saturday, demanding bolder action on climate protection from negotiators at the city's Bella Convention Center.
Protesters said 100,000 people had joined the event, while police estimates were closer to around 25,000.
The event was relatively peaceful, although a handful of masked activists detonated small explosive devices near some downtown government buildings.
On a day when little was happening at the UN-sponsored climate negotiations, thousands of activists marched through the city with banners reading "There is no planet B" in English and one in Spanish declaring "The Earth says "Enough."
Some stars joined the protest, including Danish model, photographer Helena Christensen, who said traveling to Peru, her mother's country of birth, made her aware of the heartbreaking problems the country is facing due to the already noticeable effects of climate change.
That's part of the motivation why I decided to join the big demonstration — to pass the word on and appeal to world leaders to come up with a fair, ambitious and binding agreement, she said.
It is not an easy task, but it must be done now and there is no way around it.
Police stopped protesters from getting too close to the Bella center, saying they arrested 19 people, mainly due to the fact that they were either masked or carrying pocket knives.
According to Danish law, these actions are prohibited during demonstrations.
According to a bystander, who asked not to be named because he is involved in the climate negotiations, masked protesters dressed in black detonated several explosive devices near Copenhagen's main canal, near which several ministries are located.
They threw them near the buildings, he said, adding that they started as flares but were then followed by "a few big explosions."
Inside the convention center, people gathered in front of television screens to watch the demonstration all afternoon.
But the protest has apparently failed to reach the consciousness of key officials, such as Su Wie, China's chief climate negotiator.
When asked if he thought the demonstration would have a constructive effect on international deliberations, he replied in English: "That's something I wasn't even aware of."
He then continued in Mandarin, saying, "Because the venue is big, I can't hear what's happening outside."
He noted that whether the demonstration would harm or help depends on the individual's perspective.
It shows the focus of the general public and various sectors on the issue of climate change, he said.
On the other hand, "you can also say that they interfere with negotiations or other people's freedom."
Exam data show stubborn racial divide
The math transcripts were welcome good news for Washington D.C. public schools last week.
Although Washington District still lags far behind the country's top-performing schools, the reports show that fourth- and eighth-graders have made faster progress over the past two years than cities that include Atlanta, Chicago, and New York.
But what is included in the latest figures from the National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP) is the persistent achievement gap between African-American and white students, both locally and nationally.
The average score of white fourth-graders from Washington, D.C., rose from 262 to 270 (on a scale of 500) over the past two years, but that of their African-American peers rose only three points from 209 to 212.
In reality, the performance gap increased from 53 to 58 points between 2007 and 2009.
The progress of African-American eighth-graders remained basically the same, falling by a statistically negligible point from 245 to 244.
The average score of white students was not included in the test data because the sample size was not large enough.
The picture over a six-year period is no more encouraging.
The gap that separated white and black fourth-graders in 2003, when the first NAEP was captured in this district, was 60 scale points (262 to 202).
And although the score achieved by children from both groups has grown over this period, the difference has hardly diminished to 58 points.
Some of the district's education advocates expressed concern last week that the findings, celebrated by school chancellor Michelle A. Rhee and Democratic Mayor Adrian M. Fenty, were largely driven by white students who are already high-performing children.
"This suggests that we've raised the overall score by treating those at the higher end of the scale, which is problematic and difficult," said Jeff Smith, a board member of D.C. Voice, a nonprofit that advocates for educational equality in Washington, D.C.
"I'm not jumping up and down for a range of two or three points," said Democratic Washington City Council member Kwame R. Brown, who has a fourth-grade daughter at Eaton Elementary School.
Brown, a frequent critic of Rhee's management style, said the message of exam scores is that the city's middle schools desperately need attention.
Of course, you always want to see the positive signs, I respect that.
But what scares me is that we don't spend anywhere near the time and energy we would have to spend on our middle school.
Rhee said the district must continue to find better ways to meet the needs of low-achieving students.
This fall, for example, some teachers will be trained to use a new reading curriculum, the Wilson Reading System, which targets students in the upper grades of elementary and middle school who have not mastered basic reading skills early in their school careers and who are significantly behind their peers classmates.
Everyday math, a curriculum that emphasizes games and real-life experiences from kindergarten to sixth grade, was brought to Washington under former principal school inspector Clifford Janey, and this curriculum is credited with some of the NAEP advances reported last week.
"I think we need to keep working to get the best measures for students who are below grade levels," Rhee said.
Others say the NAEP findings highlight the question of whether Rhee can continue to improve the overall performance of the system while continuing to provide the extra money and resources needed for low-performing schools to narrow the gap.
This is a serious dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, a professor of education at the University of California, Berkeley, who studies urban exam scores.
The conventional remedy is to direct one's resources and management reforms toward schools located in the poorest areas of Washington D.C.
The objective could provoke political repercussions that work against this important agenda item.
The weak point, of course, as with other city school inspectors, is that it tries to keep the white and black middle class.
Our focus is to make sure we build a system of great schools.
We need to strengthen our neighborhood schools so that all families, regardless of where they live, can be sure that their children can receive an excellent public education.
Janey, who is now a school inspector in Newark, said in an interview this week that one of the most significant elements to closing the achievement gap is to extend the traditional public school year, which is currently 180 days in Washington, to compete with charter schools.
You have to increase the school year to nearly 200 days to have the power to change, said Janey, who reached an agreement with his teachers' union last year on 185 days a year, which he sees as "a milestone" on the road to a bigger increase in the next contract.
Higher education for more people as a prospect for the future
The coach arrives at Gettysburg College with a loud whistle.
Graciela Rodriguez, 12, gets out and blinks for a moment at the sight of the white columns, brick facades and emerald lawn.
Graciela's parents barely graduated from high school in El Salvador.
Until recently, Graciela, who was recovered in Silver Spring and now lives in Riverdale, had never set foot on a college campus.
Her attitude, and that of the other eighth-graders in the group exploring Gettysburg, where classes cost $38,690 a year, was more that of an awe-inspiring visitor than that of an enthusiastic future student.
"Yes! Here I will be soon!" cried Graciela, who would like to study medicine, when the guide announced that they had now entered the natural sciences building.
"Wow, really?" she said thoughtfully when told about the school's low professor-to-student ratio.
College in Pennsylvania was the 7th the kids visited on their three-day tour, and now they've fully absorbed the intended message: The question is not whether to go to college.
The question is where.
On the one hand, there is growing concern about the large number of U.S.-born children of Hispanic immigrants who do not finish high school or become pregnant as teenagers, but there are also hundreds of thousands who are receiving the college education needed to move up into the middle class.
In truth, one in five of these "second generation" Hispanics graduate from college — which is a remarkable achievement since many of their immigrant parents, mostly from Mexico or Central America, came to the U.S. without graduating from high school.
Their success stories are important, researchers say, because they point the way forward for a generation that will play a huge role in the country's workforce.
Those who study high-performing children say they often have a natural affinity for school and an inherent drive to succeed.
Many of them also have parents who set high goals for their children and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools.
But counseling programs also play a big role in helping Graciela and millions of children like her get into college, especially if those efforts persist for an extended period of time.
If you look at low-income children whose parents don't have the experience and skills to help them navigate the system, then at some point a single measure won't solve the problem either, said Patricia Gándara, a researcher at the University of California, Davis who studied Hispanic American students.
We need to think about providing a supportive network for these children from preschool to high school.
The federal program that funded Graciela's college tour is a useful example.
It's known as GEAR UP—shifting up a gear—and allocates more than $300 million a year to local school systems to launch college prep programs that begin when low-income students are in middle school and continue until they graduate from high school.
According to the U.S. Department of Education, the program has helped more than 10 million students since 1999, more than 60% of whom went on to college.
Iraqi Oil Ministry signs contracts with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite concerns about violence and political instability, the Iraqi government has been able to persuade major oil companies to rebuild its damaged infrastructure in two auctions concluded on Saturday.
The Iraqi Oil Ministry's 10 contracts signed with foreign oil companies suggest that China, Russia and European oil companies are poised to play an important role in restructuring Iraq's oil industry, which has been paralyzed by war and economic sanctions for decades.
American companies were only able to record shares in two of the 10 auctioned fields.
Seven American companies had paid to participate in the second auction, which began on Friday.
The only company that submitted a bid lost out.
Two American companies were able to conclude contracts for fields auctioned in June.
The sparse representatives of American oil multinationals in opening up the Iraqi oil industry surprised analysts.
Iraq has finally opened its doors after 6 years of war and instead of US companies, Asian and European companies are leading the way, said Ruba Husari, the editor of Iraq Oil Forum, an online news service.
There will be no further offers in Iraq for a long time.
Security concerns, underscored by massive coordinated bombardments on Tuesday, and political instability caused by the withdrawal of the U.S. military have likely discouraged American oil companies, analysts said, from increasing their exposure to Iraq, which has the world's third-largest proven crude reserves.
U.S. firms have been disadvantaged in some cases because competitors, especially the Chinese and other state-controlled energy companies, have significantly lower labor costs and are more likely to take risks because they are not accountable to shareholders.
Exxon-Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only American companies able to sign contracts with the department.
Major US companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, which have close ties with Iraq's oil ministry and have provided technical advice in recent years, have come away empty-handed.
Russian companies Lukoil and Gazprom were the main players in two of the contracts awarded this weekend.
The state-owned China National Petroleum Corporation bid for more contracts than any other company and was able to go home with large packages of contracts for two larger fields.
We all know, said Oil Ministry spokesman Assam Jihad, that China is on its way to becoming one of the big players in the global economy as well as a technology power.
We are convinced that the Chinese company will be able to compete with its competitors and meet its commitments to Iraq.
Companies pre-selected for bidding submitted bids, which were then compared to the fee per barrel of oil that the ministry was willing to pay to increase the output of each field beyond current levels.
Top Al Qaeda Planners Apparently Killed in Pakistan
In an apparent US missile attack along Pakistan's border with Afghanistan, a top al Qaeda mission planner was reportedly killed this week, US counterterrorism officials reported on Friday.
This, if confirmed, would be the second deadly attack on a senior official of the terrorist organization this fall.
Saleh al-Somali was one of two Arabs reportedly killed by a number of missiles that hit their vehicle near the town of Miran Shah in North Waziristan province on Tuesday, according to U.S. sources and Pakistani officials in the region.
Local authorities reported that the missiles were fired by a type of drone used by the CIA in Pakistan's lawless tribal belt.
They were driving in a white vehicle toward the Afghan border when the car was hit, a Pakistani civilian intelligence official from Miran Shah said by phone.
Locals suspected of being militants ran to the site and quickly took whatever was left of the "completely destroyed bodies."
Local authorities were unable to confirm the identities of the victims, but two U.S. counterterrorism officials cited vague evidence that Somali was among the dead.
Somali has been described as al Qaeda's top military planner, directing terrorist group operations outside the Afghanistan-Pakistan region.
He was involved in conspiracies around the world, noted a senior official who wished to remain anonymous, referring to the sensitive nature of the US airstrikes on Pakistani soil.
Taking its central role for granted, this included planning attacks against the US and Europe.
He took strategic instructions from al Qaeda's top leaders and translated them into operational planning for possible terrorist attacks.
The second American official said that Somali had quickly risen in the al-Qaeda hierarchy and had excellent ties to other extremist groups in the region.
He may not be known to some Americans, the second official said, but this in no way diminishes the danger he posed to us and our allies.
If his death is confirmed, Somali would become the second senior al Qaeda or Taliban leader killed since September, when a similar attack killed Najmuddin Jalolov, the leader of a militant faction in the tribal area, and three other top activists.
The pace of attacks by CIA drones has slowed from an average of six operations per month to two since the summer, according to a summary by the Long War Journal, a website maintained by a nonprofit organization.
The decline may be due to improved tactics by terrorist groups that have taken steps to reduce their vulnerability while brutally killing suspected informants, the site reported.
Leading UN envoy in Kabul will resign
The UN's top envoy to Afghanistan, Kai Eide, said on Friday that he would step down from office in March, ending a stormy term marred by allegations of widespread corruption in the UN-backed Afghan presidential election.
The oath's departure comes as the Obama administration decided to send another 30,000 US troops to Afghanistan.
The UN envoy said he supports the troop increase, but he also expressed concern that the U.S. timetable for military withdrawal, due to begin in 18 months, could prompt other NATO governments to withdraw their forces.
We need to accelerate the build-up of the Afghan security forces and thereby send the right signal to the Afghans that they can trust the international community, Eide said in a telephone interview from Kabul.
The commitment must be long-term.
The Norwegian diplomat also urged the United States and other military powers to increase the number of international civilian aid workers to help with Afghanistan's political transition.
The troop increase on the military side must correspond to an increase on the civilian side, he said.
Eide said that he was not stepping down, but was only fulfilling an agreement made to his family in March 2008 to stay in Kabul for only two years.
He said he wanted to send the notification to the UN
Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon now so that he has time to find a replacement.
What I've said is that he'd better start looking for a successor, Eide said.
When I came here, there was a two-month vacuum between the departure of my predecessor and my arrival.
Ban has begun the search for a replacement, according to UN officials.
The UN officials say he has considered Swedish-Italian-born Staffan di Mistura, who recently headed the UN mission in Baghdad, and Frenchman Jean-Marie Guéhenno, who previously headed UN peacekeeping operations.
Eide's position in Afghanistan was tested after his former deputy, Peter W. Galbraith, accused him in September of favoring President Hamid Karzai in the country's presidential election and covering up evidence of massive electoral fraud.
Eide has denied all accusations, but he also said that the allegations made by Galbraith – who was fired – "undoubtedly caused damage to the mission because there was already a great deal of skepticism about international interference in the election."
Eide said he recommended the appointment of a senior civilian representative to coordinate aid efforts by U.S.-led forces in Afghanistan.
He also urged the UN leadership to allow his successor to hire more personnel from the United States and other Western countries to donate to the Afghan mission, saying this would boost their confidence that their money is being used properly.
Eide expressed disappointment at the reduction of his forces in Afghanistan, saying that the cumbersome UN hiring arrangements have undermined his ability to bring in capable people.
The UN rules are designed in such a way that since May, he said, I have only been able to hire one person.
This is catastrophic and must not be allowed to continue.
US Secretary of Defense Gates: Iran must expect additional sanctions
Defense Secretary Robert M. Gates said Friday that world powers will soon impose "significant additional sanctions" on Iran for not participating in talks on its nuclear plans.
Gates spoke to a group of about 300 U.S. troops in northern Iraq during a 7-day trip through the war zones in Afghanistan and Iraq, downplaying the prospect of military action against the Islamic Republic of Iran.
There are no good options for choice in Iran, he said in response to a soldier's question about the likelihood of such a development.
"One of the things that sticks on my mind is, if we've learned anything from Iraq in the last six years, the unpredictability inherent in war."
The Obama administration is considering a package of sanctions targeting Iran's military and political elite, but Gates has announced that some sanctions could also affect the average Iranian.
He said a "package of positive and negative incentives" is needed "to convince the Iranian government that it is actually less protected with nuclear weapons" because "its people will suffer tremendously" from the sanctions.
On Friday, in a statement from White House spokesman Robert Gibbs, the US administration joined European leaders in warning that Iran faces "credible" consequences if it does not comply with the demands of the UN Security Council and its nuclear watchdog, the International Atomic Energy Agency, with its nuclear program.
Iran continues to claim that knowledge of nuclear technology should only be obtained for peaceful purposes.
At talks in Geneva on Oct. 1, Iran said it would resume talks to curb its nuclear program and give up a substantial portion of its stockpile of enriched uranium in exchange for much-needed nuclear fuel for its medical research reactor.
The U.S. government has pushed for this type of agreement to build trust between the two parties and buy time for negotiations.
But Iran appears to have since abandoned negotiations on the interim agreements -- in part, experts say, because Iran's leaders are divided over whether they should commit to the United States.
Iran's simple abandonment of the international community on some proposals they agreed to in early October has, frankly, brought the international community, including the Russians and Chinese, together in ways they never were in conjunction with important additional sanctions on Iran, Gates said.
President Obama has set Dec. 31 as the deadline for Iran to respond to these proposals before pursuing other options, including what Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton once called "crushing sanctions."
In a statement issued in New York, Iran's mission to the United Nations condemned what it on Thursday called "baseless and unsubstantiated claims" by some Security Council members about Iran's nuclear activities, saying it stands ready to continue talks with the United States and five other world powers "to reach an appropriate long-term solution."
Gates, who was due to return to Washington last Friday, met with Iraqi Prime Minister Nouri al-Maliki in the morning before flying to Iraq's oil-rich Kurdish region for meetings with soldiers in Kirkuk and Kurdish officials in Irbil.
Tensions between the Kurds and the Arab majority in Iraq remain high, particularly over borders, property rights and public revenue sharing.
Gates urged both sides to reduce the potential for conflict to avoid delays in U.S. plans to reduce American troop levels from 115,000 to 50,000 by the end of August.
Gates also tried to allay Kurdish concerns about the impending troop withdrawal. U.S. officials quoted Gates as telling Masoud Barzani, president of the Kurdistan Regional Government, "We will maintain your security, prosperity and autonomy within a united Iraq.
We will not leave you."
A change of course in aging China
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters lecturing that "Mother Earth is too tired to entertain more children" and "One more baby means one more grave."
They learned these lessons so well that when government officials in Shanghai, who suddenly began to change course this summer due to the low birth rate and aging population, encouraging young couples to have more than one child, their answer was immediate and definitive: "No way."
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
There's nothing left for a second child, said Wang, 31, a human resources manager with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, which produced two generations of notoriously fat, spoiled only children affectionately called "little emperors," a population crisis is looming in the country.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple, compared to 6 when this policy came into force, according to the UN
In 2020, the number of people aged 60 and over is expected to explode from 16.7 per cent of the population to 31.1 per cent by 2050. This is far above the global average of about 20 percent.
The imbalance is greater in rich coastal cities with educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and older accounted for nearly 22 percent of Shanghai's registered residents, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai Urban Population and Family Planning Commission, has said that couples of reproductive age must have babies to "help reduce the ratio of aging populations and alleviate the labor shortage of the future."
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- though not as rich -- as developed countries like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
Enshrined in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is arguably the most controversial order introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Married couples who violate this policy face huge fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplace.
Chinese officials have credited this policy with avoiding the critical use of the country's natural resources, while human rights advocates have condemned abuses in policy enforcement.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to have abortions.
Many couples had also had sex-selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government officials have gradually weakened their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were only children -- and in 2007, the tone of many harsh slogans was softened.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Peking University's Institute of Population Research, said government officials have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children where one partner is an only child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city in July to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births.
Posters lecturing families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines detailing who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for approval.
The city government has sent city employees and family planning volunteers to visit couples at home and push information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial counseling for those who have more than one child.
The response wasn't exactly encouraging, family planning officials said.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a small rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai said there was an upswing in applications from couples wanting a second child after the campaign launched, urban districts, on the other hand, reported no change.
For example, Huinan Township, with a population of 115,000, still receives only four to five applications per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the number of births expected in the city in 2010 will still be around 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of Shanghai Caolu Township, said financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don't want to have more children.
They want to give their first one the best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would like to have two children and that this is legally allowed.
But, like many Chinese, they have only minimal government health and life insurance.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West mistakenly view the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with their first child.
Yes, we are robbed of the opportunity to have more than one child.
But the problem is not simply in politics.
The problem is money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the human resources manager, said she only wanted a child because she was also an only child. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us.
We're not used to caring for others and we don't really want to."
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it more bluntly.
For middle-class parents with dual careers that reduce the birth rate, he said, it's all about being successful and you have to be selfish for that.
Today's 20-39 age group grew up watching their parents struggle during the early days of China's capitalism experiment, and they don't want such a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, places huge demands on the time of the parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the question of space -- "You have to remodel your apartment" -- and life planning -- "When the child is 9 months old, you have to have a resume ready for the best preschools."
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to achieve a higher standard of living, he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
UN group drafts plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- hitherto characterized by wild posturing and mutual accusations -- refocused on Friday with the release of a document outlining ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with developed nations bearing the heaviest burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, has both identified the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it was seen as a major step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, as more than 100 world leaders will arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, drafted by a dedicated UN working group, is silent on the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key questions, including how developed and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and what the upper limit of global temperature rise should be that policymakers would support.
The process will be given great flexibility, according to John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate change official, Yvo de Boer, has called "the big picture."
It shows the outline of a possible agreement in which the industrialized nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, the countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also boosted Friday's talks by pledging to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change, from coping with floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Friday nevertheless brought the same verbal fireworks that had dominated last week's talks.
US Special Representative for Climate Change Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for developed countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, if they are not financed by developed countries.
This move announced that the Obama administration was taking a harder line with China than Bush administration officials did less than two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without major emerging economies standing up and taking action, Stern said, who also complained that the text did not go far enough to ensure that the cuts could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern made his statement an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei's statement that the top American climate negotiator either lacked "reason" or was "highly irresponsible" of him for saying earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China cope with global warming.
With the future economic direction of the major world powers at stake, fault lines have opened up both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging economies.
The current struggle is equally about saving individual economies and saving the planet, with China and the United States feuding over their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific need to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that the major powers are fighting over who should bear the cost of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved to be more aggressive in holding countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic dominance will develop, according to Ulate, who also serves as a regional climate change advisor for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although leading participants say the talks will, at best, lead to a political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States presented a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who chairs the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said the small island states' offensive "puts political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now united and demanding action from emerging economies such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most outstanding issues need to be resolved before the arrival of government leaders in order to reach an agreement.
Senior officials, such as India's Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China's Vice Minister, got off their planes and raced through the corridors of the Bella Center for closed-door meetings and press conferences to stake out claims that will be negotiated over the next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people come and go of the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists put on nightly shows mocking the countries they think are betraying and selling each other, and draft contracts are passed from hand to hand rather than by email -- is already challenging.
The intensity is only just building up: almost all the key ministers are here now, and from Wednesday 60 government leaders will be in Copenhagen.
We are coming to the top league, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president of global politics at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
Britain's first 225km/h train redefines the Monday feeling
Monday morning at 5:13 a.m., a whistle will pierce the darkness to announce a train departure that represents a revolution in transport in the UK.
The country's first high-speed commuter train will reach 225 km/h on its lightning journey from Ashfort, Kent, to London St Pancras, covering 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lady Kelly Holmes will then board the first Javelin commuter service from London to Lord Adonis, the Minister for Transport.
He hopes that the new service will eventually connect Britain to an international rail network of fast, reliable trains and connect the major metropolitan areas of the Midlands, North and Scotland to London.
The neglected province could become vibrant commuter cities, commute times would be radically reduced, and switching from plane and car to rail would reduce national carbon emissions and road congestion.
In theory, the three major parties believe in this vision.
But the many billions of British pounds needed to build a new national rail network, the inevitable planning battle and fears of environmental damage could still put the brakes on Britain's high-speed tracks.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company set up in January to submit a feasibility study to the government, will deliver the report to Lord Adonis on Dec. 30, according to the Times.
This will provide him with a detailed route map of the next planned stage of the high-speed rail network.
The new rail line, which will connect London to the West Midlands, will have a five-metre headway past urban areas and places where the impact on the environment is controversial.
In open terrain, the plan will demonstrate the concept within 25 meters of the final track.
HS2 will also create three options for a larger, northbound high-speed rail network.
Lord Adonis will respond in the spring.
The preferred proposed option is a Y-shaped route, where a single high-speed line would lead into the West Midlands.
The line would split in or near Birmingham and one branch would run west of the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another north-east to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line would lead to Scotland.
"It seems to be the best working option," said a railway insider.
Once completed, travel time between London and Edinburgh would be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first leg, which would not open before 2025, would allow travellers to cover the London-Birmingham route in 49 minutes, compared to just over an hour today.
The designs would allow trains to travel at a speed of 400 km/h, making the British rail network the fastest in Europe.
The first route was planned so that 400-meter-long trains with a maximum capacity of 1,100 people could run on it.
Up to 18 trains per hour could operate on the London-Birmingham line.
This, in turn, would mean that London would need a terminus that could handle 20,000 passengers per hour.
Given the spatial constraints in the capital, it is expected that an existing station would be upgraded to accommodate the high-speed network.
Rail experts say only St. Pancras International or Euston have this potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks this plan should continue, but the lengthy public consultation and planning means that a final decision will not be taken until after the general election.
But even if he sets the wheels in motion, the rail network must be built in sections.
Trains would first have to switch from the high-speed lines to existing rail lines in north Birmingham, which would still keep the journey time between London and Scotland at over three hours.
This is considered a crucial sticking point to ensure a change from aircraft to rail, a benchmark for the rail revolution.
