Dream Worlds
Some see images while awake and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
The boundaries between imagination and reality are blurred, not only in the mentally ill and in drug intoxication.
As long as it happens in your sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we are allowed to indulge uninhibitedly in the wildest imaginations and fantasies.
However, anyone who experiences dreamlike states while awake, sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is usually considered crazy or drug addict in the modern Western world, at least as an oddball.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or in drug intoxication.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that enable us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels sometimes blur the boundaries between dream, delusion and reality.
Dream-like altered waking states of consciousness can occur in a variety of forms, at best we call them visions, at worst delusions.
Even if the trigger and effect may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic raptures, psychoses and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of the neuronal messengers of the brain - above all dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine - is derailed and the interaction of different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts very often occur during schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity no longer has any power over him
The connection between delusion and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since antiquity.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of dream in the waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great similarity of madness with dream states", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the inconsistencies, delusions, sensory illusions of such".
It is autumn 2001 when Henning T. transforms into a cartoon character.
His body is two-dimensional and brightly colored.
Gravity no longer has any power over him, he floats on the ceiling.
He feels a kick.
Behind him winged devil figures with blood-red, distorted grimaces, baring their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Loud, malicious voices boom from walls and radio.
He can no longer stand them, the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. tears two cables out of the stereo, knots them into a noose and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs onto a loudspeaker and puts the noose around his neck.
Jumps.
The noose loosens.
This should be a lesson to you, the voices scream in eardrum-shredded chorus, "Go to the clinic and let yourself be healed!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last one was 2 years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
It was caused by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, he takes medication for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis, I experienced the worst fear and deepest despair, he says.
The mirages are cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in a lifetime, in psychiatric hospitals it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, sufferers can usually no longer distinguish between the inner and outer world, they get into an overexcited state, which can lead to hallucinations, megalomania, relationship or paranoia.
Hearing voices is particularly widespread - voices that command, comment or dialog.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The affected person is no longer able to separate the important from the unimportant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis opens the floodgates for a flood of ideas and fantasies that originate from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, he is, similar to the dream, overwhelmed by the events and can not actively shape them.
Schizophrenics therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
A reality comparison is usually not possible for them, the mirages are cruel reality, waking up excluded.
To have experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in dreams, says Fuchs, "the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, is fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in the real framework.
Why exactly our brain beats capers is still a mystery to researchers.
States of emergency can cause every person to lose touch with reality for a short time, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the sole determinants.
Researchers assume that there is minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, for example by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery how the disruption of the neural system comes about, which also does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be triggers for psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychosis because they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brain is running hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get some, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether mirages are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and deceptions for ten years, and last year he evaluated his findings in the book "The Unreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are one of the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of an astonishing number of other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's disease and craniocerebral trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brains of healthy people hallucinate.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are composed of memory content that is normally held back.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or insufficiently inhibited; when our brain is running hot or when stimulation is missing.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also stimulus withdrawal, stress, lovesickness or other mental states of emergency.
In recent studies, up to one-third of respondents said they had experienced hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends high school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If it weren't for the pictures and voices.
During the break, it may happen that a lanky boy with long, dark hair addresses it.
When it answers him, the classmates look at it in surprise - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spun daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows that.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bank next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy?, she sometimes wonders.
But she knows that this boy and the other mirages are not real and disappear again.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening
Often the mirages are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the lesson material because the teacher is introducing a new classmate in her eyes and ears, while he explains mathematical equations on the blackboard for everyone else to hear and see.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening.
When she waits in her dark room for sleep, which comes far too rarely and far too late, she often cannot distinguish whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the images she sees, the grimaces or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, appear in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she shouts at the figures.
She doesn't tell parents and friends about it, they think she's crazy.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated from high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she contacted the psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows exactly that she is not crazy.
Delusion is also a work of art out of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from stimulus deprivation, they are very likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I suspect that the brain is then underemployed and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when, at 13, she learned that the man she has called Papa for as long as she can remember is not her biological father.
Since the same brain areas are active in visual and auditory hallucinations that also process real impressions and sounds, sufferers like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between illusions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is depicted there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain creates, which is why they seem so real."
Kasten also sees nocturnal dream images as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
In contrast to schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their mirages as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to appreciate the hallucinations as a special ability.
Borderline state between dream and hallucination
In our too consciousness-centered world, imaginary experience is unfortunately usually pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a serious, painful illness, but it also contains positive, creative things - delusion is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of dream-like altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer considers real and that he cannot distinguish from the waking state even in retrospect.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma- or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
If a person is threatened by loss of self and the world, for example by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own, imaginary world that is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline state between dream and hallucination.
Since coping with a situation is not possible in reality, a change of world takes place, but the real situation is visualized in the imagination.
An intensive form of creating meaning and giving meaning in an inherently unbearable situation, which allows us humans our own creative ability not to perish in a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" as a rescue operation of the soul.
He was 49 years old when his consciousness traveled for days after heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, while his body was condemned to immobility in the intensive care unit.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, on board a train anatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who make intoxicants from blood.
Is kidnapped by a Greek on a motorcycle to his home country, surfs with his hospital bed in the firn snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
He is completely absorbed in the imagined events, everything is real, even later in memory.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental journeys are still abundantly clear to me years and in minor details.
Clearer and more intense even than what has really been experienced.
The intensity of this experience goes beyond the horizon of our other life-world experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroids, psychosis, hallucinations and drug intoxication show how fragile our inner images of external reality are even when we are awake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, the psychologist Kasten sums up, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
