75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of the study "Fertility and career of women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged between 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities on the labour market limited due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are big differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and, if so, what kind of profession they have.
Those of them who do no other work outside the home, work only part-time or do not have a permanent employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with permanent jobs, especially in the public sector, postpone starting a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the age group between 35 and 49 with a permanent job do not have their first child on average until 3.7 years after moving in together, a figure that increases to 4.1 years for women with permanent jobs who took longer to achieve this and who moved in together and did not realize their first child until much later.
In addition, the type of work has a great influence on motherhood, although less than the calendar in terms of readiness to conceive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account when it comes to the age of women at marriage and having their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference was also observed in women of the same age.
For example, women in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, depending on whether they only have a lower secondary school leaving certificate or higher education, became mothers for the first time on average at 25.1 or 32.1 respectively.
There is also another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While women with a high degree marry and have their first child before their first permanent position, women with a middle or high school diploma do it the other way around and first look for a permanent job and then marry and then have their first child, Delgado notes.
