The task of the Emergency Brake Assist is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre, which the system detects based on the braking force applied by the driver to the brake pedal.
However, this system does not exert this pressure to the end.
According to a study commissioned by the components manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even get to step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked at full speed.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system, thereby reducing the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during braking.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented every year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - it is estimated that one in four accidents involving personal injury could be prevented - once the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not react to the warning, and even if the collision is already unavoidable, Brake Assist applies maximum pressure to the brakes in order to minimise the damage.
