Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is anything but easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Audatex Sales Manager, it works with 63 manufacturers and importers, each of them providing the information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is getting bigger and bigger, to the point that in the last five years even more versions, variants and engines came onto the market than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car comes onto the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a tedious task, because each of the thousands of vehicle parts has to be catagolized and its price entered.
In addition, an "intelligent" graphic image is created of each model, on which you can "click" on different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much-selling model, the work can be completed in a week if the process proceeds quickly.
If it's a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In terms of vehicle fleets on the roads, the figure is over 99%.
Audatex has eight centres around the world (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) for the purpose of carrying out documentation and database work, each of which specialises in specific brands.
The national headquarters are located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanical specialists) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in the development of these databases.
Every month they record 2.5 million pieces of data and their customers get the updates every other day.
The elaboration of this enormous flow of information allows companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap parts or for calculating the commercial or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain, but in the United States.
By reviewing the products Audatex offers, it's easy to get an overview of the kind of support it gives industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, with the star of the products being AudaPlus, a standard accident assessment solution for assessors.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles and light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the painting prices.
This tool is paid according to the intended use, i.e. for each appraisal.
It will be most expensive for customers who rarely use it, a maximum of ten times a month, namely 5.75 euros per month.
On the other hand, any insurance company that produces thousands of appraisals negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, you can fully identify a vehicle and the equipment with which it rolled off the assembly line by the chassis number alone.
AudaGlass deals with vehicle windows, and AudaSubastas is a service on the Internet open to the specialist market, with which you can bid for vehicles that have been declared a total loss.
Their statistics service is very useful in identifying trends, carrying out geodemographic analyses or obtaining information on deviations by brand and model.
It can be used, for example, to examine how many models of a certain car brand had to go to the workshop due to breakdowns or how many of them were involved in a serious accident in a certain period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of computer tools.
It distributes, among others, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for appraisers and provides digital images, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer in the same way.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, breakdown and maintenance of vehicles.
The GT Guide to Appraisals is a reference product on the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 appraisers and 53 insurance companies.
Its business volume has increased by 20% annually over the last three years and in 2008 the turnover amounted to 10.8 million euros.
At the beginning of last year, they began to enter the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to the company's sources, 62% of its business is done in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America. They work with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, 3,000 of them in Spain.
The total turnover in the world of the Solera Group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) amounts to 557 million dollars, 3.35 more than in 2008.
In Germany, the company has revenues of 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was worth $1 billion on the stock exchange, and today its shares are valued at $2.4 billion.
Since 2007, they have been listed on the New York Stock Exchange and are part of the benchmark index Standard & Poor's.
Auction of crashed cars on the Internet
Last October, the Solera Autoonline group bought a platform on the Internet for the sale of accident vehicles and motorcycles.
This purchase meant the payment of 59.5 million euros for 85% of the company's capital, which could increase to the remaining 15% next year.
The purpose of this purchase was to offer more services and value to its customers, with the possibility of gaining access to a huge international market.
This appraisal and purchase service is aimed exclusively at industry professionals, such as insurance companies, appraisers, car rental companies, workshops, scrapyards and car dealers, who must register before their activities.
This platform was founded in Germany in 1996 and manages more than 650,000 operations across Europe, 500,000 of them in Germany alone.
Its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
The site now has more than 1,500 registered sellers and 4,000 reviewers.
Every day, 3,000 ads are managed and 100 new ads are added to the Spanish market every day.
According to Spanish legislation, a vehicle whose chassis number has been deregistered may no longer drive on the roads, but certain undamaged parts may be used as spare parts.
Cars with historical value, on the other hand, may be re-registered, even if they have been deregistered after difficult administrative procedures.
Cost estimate of the workshop in four steps
With the Auda-Taller tool, Audatex ensures that the user receives a quote in just four steps: identification of the vehicle, search for the spare part, preparation and preparation of a quote.
The ease of use of these systems is a fundamental condition, especially in order to convince older professionals who are usually more or less opposed to the use of these new computer techniques.
The database contains 1,034 vehicles, 666 of which are passenger cars, 109 off-road vehicles, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Of course, you need a computer with an internet connection to use it.
After the model to be repaired has been identified by the chassis number, a graphic of the respective model appears and then the required spare part is selected.
The user can include variables such as the price for the working hours, surcharges or discounts and then he can have the estimate printed and passed on to his customer.
However, AudaTaller is not a tool for assessment like AudaPlus, but rather a reference catalog.
The main difference between the two systems is that the one focused on the workshop does not include estimated working hours.
The cost of using this tool is 350 euros per year, an amount that the customer can easily pay.
Currently, the company Audatex is working on being able to offer these images in three-dimensional format.
This is an innovation that car mechanics have been waiting for a long time, as it allows you to select a door, for example, and then completely flip the image to look at the inside.
